Principal Component Analysis

Dataset water.zostera.all.scaled

This dataset contains 31 individuals and 9 variables, 1 qualitative variable is considered as illustrative.

1. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of PCA express 63.68% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 63.68% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is relatively high and thus the first plane well represents the data variability. This value is greater than the reference value that equals 48.48%, the variability explained by this plane is thus significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 675 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it should be better to also interpret the dimensions greater or equal to the third one.

Figure 1 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the PCA

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 1 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (44.45% against 29.1%). This observation suggests that only this axis is carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

2. Description of the dimension 1

Figure 2.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction.

The Wilks test p-value indicates which variable factors are the best separated on the plane (i.e.which one explain the best the distance between individuals).

##   station 
## 0.2945784

There only is one possible qualitative variable to illustrate the distance between individuals : station.

Figure 2.2 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction. The individuals are coloured after their category for the variable station.

Figure 2.3 - Variables factor map (PCA) The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.

Figure 2.4 - Qualitative factor map (PCA) The labeled factors are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as 26 (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as 19 (to the left of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individual 26 stands (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables NO3, Ninorg, seston, PO4, NH4 and chl_a (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The group in which the individual 19 stands (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • low values for the variables Ntotal, NH4 and Ninorg (variables are sorted from the weakest).

3. Classification

Figure 3 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 5 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals sharing :

  • low values for the variables Ntotal, chl_a, NH4 and Ninorg (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as 17, 19 and 23. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variable chl_a.

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as 9, 14, 20 and 25. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables Ntotal and secchi (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The cluster 4 is made of individuals such as 18. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables PO4 and seston (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The cluster 5 is made of individuals such as 26. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables NO3, Ninorg, seston and NH4 (variables are sorted from the strongest).
